n to be around 20 % for all source heights. For the example with <italic>&#x003c3;</italic><sub><italic>T</italic><italic>x</italic></sub>/<italic>&#x003c3;</italic><sub><italic>T</italic><italic>y</italic>,<italic>z</italic></sub>=0.45/0.3=1.5, similar to what has been seen in neocortical experiments (Goto et al. <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR21">2010</xref>), the RMS difference is reduced to about 10 %. Note also that not all of this deviation from the isotropic result stems from the anisotropy itself as also the &#x02018;average&#x02019; conductivity is altered. To complement the RMS measure which averages the deviations across many contacts, we show in panel C another deviation measure from the same data, i.e., the maximum deviation between the lead-field predictions for the various examples and the reference case, normalized by the maximum lead-field value for the reference case (corresponding to the electrode positioned immediately below the point source). Qualitatively, these deviation curves look similar to the results for the RMS measure in panel B.
